  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly:  "Apollodorus, of Athens Scholar, 2nd cent. BC, His &#x3A7;&#x3C1;&#x3BF;&#x3BD;&#x3B9;&#x3BA;&#x3AC; (Chronik&#xE1;) in four books lists historical events 
    in chronological order. Its composition in iambic trimeters was intended as a mnemonic aid. The first three books extend to 144/3, and the fourth concludes 
    the series. It was based on the &#x3A7;&#x3C1;&#x3BF;&#x3BD;&#x3BF;&#x3B3;&#x3C1;&#x3B1;&#x3C6;&#x3AF;&#x3B1;&#x3B9; (Chronograph&#xED;ai) of  Eratosthenes, which it replaced in public estimation and in its coverage. Eratosthenes
    had stopped at the death of Alexander the Great in 323; A. continues the chronicle until shortly before his own death in about 110 BC, like Eratosthenes dating the 
    fall of Troy to 1184/3, but following Ephorus in putting Homer's composition much later, in 944/3....."
    from Montanari, Franco (Pisa). "Apollodorus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and ; Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2011. 
    Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 05 October 2011   </mads:note>
